query: Answer the question in this video.
question_text:
A bead slides downward along a cycloidal track. Let a be the magnitude of its acceleration at some arbitrary point. Which relationship is correct?
(Hint: because the radius of curvature is small, a centripetal‐acceleration term is added.)
(A) a = g \sin\theta
(B) a > g \sin\theta
(C) a < g \sin\theta
(D) a = g (constant)
prediction:
If you call θ the angle the tangent to the cycloid makes with the horizontal, then the tangential component of the acceleration is 
aₜ = g sin θ. 
But the bead is also curving, so there is a normal (centripetal) acceleration 
aₙ = v²/ρ 
pointing into the curve.  Hence the total magnitude is  
a = √(aₜ² + aₙ²)  >  aₜ = g sin θ. 
Answer: (B) a > g sin θ.

question_text:
A bead released from height h travels down a cycloidal path. At the point where its speed is v, the angle is \theta. For a bead that reaches the same speed v on a straight ramp, the angle is \theta{\prime}. Which statement is correct?

prediction:

Since the cycloid is the brachistochrone (it gets you down fastest) it must, at every instant of equal speed v, be “more steep’’ in the sense that it has the larger g sin θ.  Hence

 g sin θ′ < g sin θ
⇒ θ′ < θ.

So the correct choice is

(A) θ′ < θ.
